04967nam a22007455i 9780812290172DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20132008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979685057  a97808122901727 a10.9783/97808122901722doi  a(DE-B1597)449791  a(OCoLC)874143752  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aE99.C5 ǂb Y37 2008eb 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a305.897/5571 aYarbrough, Fay A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRace and the Cherokee Nation :bSovereignty in the Nineteenth Century /cFay A. Yarbrough. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b7 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps and Tables -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. A Moment of Inclusion -- tChapter 2. Racial Ideology in Transition -- tChapter 3. The 1855 Marriage Law -- tChapter 4. The Civil War -- tChapter 5. The Cherokee Freedmen’s Story -- tChapter 6. Indian Slavery and Memory -- tChapter 7. The Fight for Recognition Continues -- tAppendix. Note on Sources and Methodology -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a"We believe by blood only," said a Cherokee resident of Oklahoma, speaking to reporters in 2007 after voting in favor of the Cherokee Nation constitutional amendment limiting its membership. In an election that made headlines around the world, a majority of Cherokee voters chose to eject from their tribe the descendants of the African American freedmen Cherokee Indians had once enslaved. Because of the unique sovereign status of Indian nations in the United States, legal membership in an Indian nation can have real economic benefits. In addition to money, the issues brought forth in this election have racial and cultural roots going back before the Civil War.Race and the Cherokee Nation examines how leaders of the Cherokee Nation fostered a racial ideology through the regulation of interracial marriage. By defining and policing interracial sex, nineteenth-century Cherokee lawmakers preserved political sovereignty, delineated Cherokee identity, and established a social hierarchy. Moreover, Cherokee conceptions of race and what constituted interracial sex differed from those of blacks and whites. Moving beyond the usual black/white dichotomy, historian Fay A. Yarbrough places American Indian voices firmly at the center of the story, as well as contrasting African American conceptions and perspectives on interracial sex with those of Cherokee Indians.For American Indians, nineteenth-century relationships produced offspring that pushed racial and citizenship boundaries. Those boundaries continue to have an impact on the way individuals identify themselves and what legal rights they can claim today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aNative American Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229017240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812290172423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812290172/original  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041349-6  Penn Press eBook Package American History  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-